nd Cameletti (2015) consider grouping data according to just one 9-levels-category factor. Data for the reasons stated before can be organized in a way such that each single observation (squares in figure below) belongs to its respective mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive categories (circles in figure). simplifing_problem Moreover data can be also conveniently partitioned into two meta-categories: fist level and second level. First level are identified by sampling observations which are drawn by the same probability distribution. Second level (circles) are categories and might be associated to a set of parameters \(	heta=\left\{	heta_{1}, \ldots, 	heta_{J}ight\}\). Since the structure is hierarchical, a DAG (Directed Acyclical Graph) (2015) representation might sort out ideas. If categories are represented by different thetas nodes \(	heta\) and edges are the logical belonging condition to the precise category then: To fully take into account the hierarchical structure of the data, \(\left\{	heta_{1}, \ldots, 	heta_{J}ight\}\) is assumed to come from a distribution \(\pi\left(	heta_{j} \mid \psiight)\) characterized by \( oldsymbol{\psi}=\left\{\psi_{1}, \ldots, \psi_{K}ight\}\) hyper parameters, left figure. If \(	heta_{j}\) come from the same distribution they are assumed also to be sharing information (Marta Blangiardo 2015). In a hierarchical framework this can be reformulated by: \[ \pi\left(	heta_{1}, \ldots, 	heta_{J} \mid \psiight)=\int \prod_{j=1}^{J} \pi\left(	heta_{j} \mid \psiight) \pi(\psi) \mathrm{d} \psi \] theta \(	heta_{j}\) parameters are similar in the sense they come from the same distribution family characterized by \( oldsymbol{\psi}\) hyper parameters, which at their own time are identified by priors (fixed quantities). This structure can extended to allow more than two levels of hierarchy since the marginal distributions of \(	heta\) can be decomposed into the product of their conditional distribution given some hyperparameter \(\psi\) as well as their prior distribution \(p(\psi)\). \[ \pi( oldsymbol{	heta})=\int \pi\left( oldsymbol{	heta} \mid  oldsymbol{\psi}_{1}ight) \pi\left( oldsymbol{\psi}_{1} \mid  oldsymbol{\psi}_{2}ight) \ldots \pi\left( oldsymbol{\psi}_{L-1} \mid  oldsymbol{\psi}_{L}ight) \pi\left( oldsymbol{\psi}_{L}ight) \mathrm{d}  oldsymbol{\psi}_{1} \ldots \mathrm{d}  oldsymbol{\psi}_{L} \] \( oldsymbol{\psi}_{l}\) identifies the hyper pram for the l th level of hierarchy. The property to enable deeper nested hyperparameters (i.e. add \(L\) hierarchy levels) is said Exchangeability and allows to extend the dimensions in which the problem in evaluated (spatio-temporal models). From a theoretical point of view there is no constraints to how many \(L\) levels to consider, as a consequence model interpretability suffers from adding too many layers. 6.5 INLA as a hierarchical model [va parafrasato] The model can be then rewritten in LGM terms following section 5.1, within the bayesian hierarchical structure. This enables INLA computation and its benefits. The first level belongs to the sampling distribution for \(y\), which are conditional to parameter and hyper parameter given the latent field \(\mathbf{	heta}\) and the hyper parameters \( oldsymbol{\psi}\): \[  oldsymbol{y} \mid  oldsymbol{	heta},  oldsymbol{\psi}_{1} \sim \pi\left( oldsymbol{y} \mid  oldsymbol{	heta},  oldsymbol{\psi}_{1}ight)=\prod_{i=1}^{n} \pi\left(y_{i} \mid 	heta_{i},  oldsymbol{\psi}_{1}ight) \] Then at the second level the latent field \( oldsymbol{	heta}\) is characterized by a multivariate Normal distribution given all the other hyper parameters \(\psi_{2}\): \[  oldsymbol{	heta} \mid  oldsymbol{\psi}_{2} \sim \mathrm{MVNormal}\left( oldsymbol{0},  oldsymbol{Q}^{-1}\left( oldsymbol{\psi}_{2}ight)ight) \] Finally, the hyperparameters \( oldsymbol{v}=\left\{\psi_{1},  oldsymbol{\psi}_{2}ight\}\) have some prior distribution given by \(\psi \sim \pi(\psi)\) 6.6 Spatial Kriging fallo da slid